	# Running the application
	
	### Option A: all-in-docker
	
	```
	cp .env.example .env
	bash start.prod.sh
	```
	
	Then open [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000) (simulator)
	
	If you see error: `no basic auth credentials`, then
	
	1. Login to AWS SSO: https://ifitsso.awsapps.com/start/
	2. Open AWS Account -> `shadowfax-sandbox` -> Command line or programmatic access
	3. Follow Option 2 to update your `~/.aws/credentials` file
	4. Run `aws ecr get-login-password --region us-east-1 --profile 756595759858_iFitPowerUserAccess | docker login --username AWS --password-stdin 756595759858.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com`
	5. Run `bash start.prod.sh`
	
	### Option B: kafka+memcached in docker; node.js runner - locally
	
	yarn start
	
	```shell
	nvm use
	cp .env.example .env
	yarn start
	
	# Start the workout
	curl -X POST http://localhost:9044/workouts/60a6d754dcd622000770946f/start -H "Authorization: $TKN"
	```
	
	### CLI Commands
	
	- `bash build.base.sh` - Build, tag and push base image to AWS ECR Registry (node.js dependencies only) - NPM_TOKEN is required in your .env file
	- `bash build.prod.sh` - Build, tag and push production image to AWS ECR Registry (runner with production dependencies only) - NPM_TOKEN is required in your .env file
	- `bash start.prod.sh` - Start all-in-docker local environment
	- `yarn kafka:logs` - Watch kafka & zookeeper logs
	- `yarn kafka:consume topic_name` - Start `topic_name` consumer (receive values from the topic)
	- `yarn kafka:produce topic_name` - Start `topic_name` producer (send values to the topic)
	  - send `[key]:[value]` pairs via the prompt that pops up
	  - ```
	    example
	    $ yarn kafka:produce workout_time_changed    # starts the producer prompt
	    > 602569fca5d90f0008ebea41:paused            # pauses the workout for session id 602569fca5d90f0008ebea41
	    ```
	- `yarn load:local` - Calls `yarn start` (unless a runner is already running locally) and then runs a very small load test of 10 workouts started over 10 seconds against your local instance of the Shadowfax runner. To change the number of workouts started update the `arrivalCount` in the `local` section of `load-test/start-workout.yml`.
	- `yarn load:test` - Runs a load test of 600 workouts started over 60 seconds against the sandbox environment. To change the number of workouts started update the `arrivalCount` in the `test` section of `load-test/start-workout.yml`.
	
	### Scripts
	
	Some scripts in the `scripts/` folder are meant to be run manually by the developer. Here's a list of those workflows.
	
	1. `timer-drift` - scripts to measure accuracy of Shadowfax's event-based timer. It does this in a few ways, see [here](https://ifitdev.atlassian.net/l/c/Q91WxMN0) for an explanation.
	   - In the root project folder, run `./scripts/timer-drift/log.sh`.
	     - This will pipe stdout/stderr into a file for analysis (the script gets the timing information from the console debug information)
	     - Note: the script provides no way to control how long the timer runs, so you'll need to Ctrl-c manually when you want to stop collecting data.
	   - After the logging process has stopped, run `./scripts/timer-drift/extract.sh`
	     - This will search the `timer-log.txt` for the timestamps related to the Shadowfax timer.
	   - Next, run `yarn script scripts/timer-drift/calculateDrift.ts`
	     - This will output a breakdown of drift-related information. The lower the drift, the more accurate the timer is.
	   - Optional: run `./scripts/timer-drift/cleanup.sh` to delete the temporary log files created by the previous scripts
	
	### Technologies/architecture
	
	- Runner: Node.js (v14), Typescript
	- Event-Broker: Kafka, Zookeeper in Docker
	- memcached
	- AWS Glue (Schema Registry)
	
